**Steps to Reproduce**:

Compile and run the following code
```cs
#nullable enable
class C
{
  public static void Main()
  {
    foreach(ref I<string> s in new RefEnumerable())
    {
      s.Prop.ToString();
    }
  }
}

interface I<out T>
{
  T Prop { get; }
}

class Test<T> : I<T>
{
  public Test(T t) => Prop = t;
  public T Prop { get; set; }
}

class RefEnumerable
{
  public RefEnumerator GetEnumerator() => new RefEnumerator();
  public class RefEnumerator
  {
    Test<string?> field = new Test<string?>(null);
    public ref Test<string?> Current => ref field;
    public bool MoveNext() => true;
  }
}
```

**Expected Behavior**:
Warning for foreach variable `ref I<string> s` as `Test<string?>` cannot be converted to `I<string>` due to nullability mismatch in type arguments

**Actual Behavior**:
No warnings. The program crashes at runtime with a null reference exception while dereferencing `s.Prop`

**Notes**
It seems that the conversion check is missing for foreach ref variables. If you remove the `ref` keyword in foreach you get the correct warning `warning CS8619: Nullability of reference types in value of type 'Test<string?>' doesn't match target type 'I<string>'.`

